				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\beta $$\end{document}β beyond 50°. However, the sidewall will block out a significant amount of area in the room and, thus, is not feasible. Additionally, as is shown in Fig. 4b, the modification of the boundary condition would not exacerbate the violation of social distancing requirement (d smaller than social distance). On the contrary, the violation is even alleviated near the bottleneck due to the asymmetry. Because of the asymmetry, one side of the individuals tend to exit with a much higher priority, and there is no close competition between individuals in the vicinity of the door.

